[Student "S"]
{Never mind the bidding. North is to play 7NT. East leads the \CQ.

You have 12 top tricks. There are no finesses available, but a 3-3 split in either Major suit will provide the 13th trick. As you can see, this is not going to happen.

But there is another possibility; if the same defender holds 4 \Hs and 4 \Ss you will be able to squeeze him in those two suits.

You win the \CK and play \H A K Q to test the \H suit, but East discards a \C on the \HQ. (You tested \Hs first because of dummy's limited entries to the \S suit.) 

Your \H2 is not a winner but is a <b>THREAT</b> to become one. West holds the \HJ which is a <b>GUARD</b> against that happening.

Next play your 4 \D winners, discarding a \C from dummy. West follows twice, then starts to feel the pressure. He cannot discard the \HJ because it is guarding your \H2, and since he can see those 4 \Ss in dummy he doesn't want to discard a \S. He discards both his \Cs, trusting East to guard that suit. 

Now you play the \CA. At this point you are still hoping the \Ss will split 3-3. They aren't going to, as you see, but something wonderful happens instead. West cannot discard his \HJ because to do so would establish your \H2. So he must throw a \S instead. You realize your \H2 is not a winner so you just play \SK, \SA and \SQ, and amazingly dummy's \S3 has become your thirteenth trick.

Of course if West had discarded his \HJ you would have cashed your \H2 and then taken three \S winners.

You just executed a Squeeze Play and you didn't even have to try. 

This type of squeeze is called an <i><b>automatic squeeze</b></i> because it operates equally well against either defender. Suppose the EW hands were switched. Of course the opening lead would have been different, but when you were ready to play your ninth winner the hands would have looked like this.

This time it is East who holds the only Guards in both \Ss and \Hs.

You play the \CA and he must give up one of those Guards.}
[Play "W"]CQ

