[Student "S"]
{East is to play 7\C. South leads the \HK.

East is to play 7\C. South leads the \HK.

You have 11 sure winners in your hand and dummy's \DQ makes 12. Your main hope is for a 3-3 \D split in which case dummy's fourth \D will be a winner.

But there is another possibility in case the \Ds don't split. Dummy's \HQ is a THREAT card which is GUARDED only by South's \HA. If it is South who has the 4 \Ds you will be able to squeeze him.

You ruff the \HK and play 5 more \C winners, being careful not to discard a \D or the \HQ from dummy.  

With everybody down to 7 cards this is the position. North's hand is important only in that he must hold on to his \S stopper. South must keep the \HA and all four \Ds.

Play the \S A K and South begins to feel the heat. 

On the \SK you discarded dummy's small \H and South also discarded a \H. 

But now you play the SQUEEZE card, the \CA. South absolutely cannot throw away his \HA, so he discards a \D instead.

Since he still has the \HA you know dummy's \HQ is useless so you discard it. Dummy's fourth \D has become a winner. 

This type of squeeze is called a <i><b>positional squeeze</b></i> because it only operates against one of the defenders. Suppose the EW hands were switched as shown below. When you were ready to play the Squeeze Card the hands would have looked like this.

North holds the only Guards in both red suits, but he cannot be squeezed.

You must play from dummy <b>BEFORE</b> North plays, so he just matches whatever you do.

If you discard the \HQ North will throw his \HA. If you discard dummy's fourth \D, North will throw his fourth \D.}
[Play "W"]HK

