{West is to play 6NT. North leads the \SK.

You have 11 winners; 1 \S, 2 \Hs, 4 \Ds and 4 \Cs. If you can make a trick with the \SJ all will be well. But if not, as long as North holds the \SQ, which is almost a certainty, you will be able to squeeze him in \Ss and \Hs. 

The first thing you should do is to duck the \SK. If North foolishly plays another \S your troubles are over. But he doesn't, he plays the \HQ instead which you win with dummy's \HK.  

Even though North didn't play a second \S your first round duck served a very important purpose - it rectified the count for your squeeze.

Next play off your 4 \D winners, discarding a small \H from your hand. 

You are now zeroing in on North.

Play the \CK, \CJ, then over to your \CQ. 

[showcards N:S7,S4,HA,H3 E:S9,S8,S6,C8 S:SA,SJ,H7,CA W:SQ,ST,HJ,H9]

Here is the layout after the 3 \C plays. Everybody followed suit except North who discarded a \H (unhappily, it seemed). 

When you now play your \CA, discarding a \S from dummy, North is squeezed.

If he discards the \ST, then his \SQ will fall underneath your \SA, establishing your \SJ.

But if he instead throws the \H9, both of dummy's \Hs will become winners.}
[Play "W"]SK

