[Student "S"]
{West is to play 6\C. North leads the \HK.

You have 11 top tricks and hope for a 3-3 \D split to give you one more. If they don't split you can hope that the defender with 4 \Ds also holds the \SK and that a squeeze will be possible.

In case the squeeze becomes necessary you should rectify the count, so you win the first trick, pull trumps in two rounds, then give up a \H trick. 

North takes the \H trick and plays the \D9 which you win with your \DQ.

You now make the key play of taking dummy's \SA before running three rounds of \Cs. 

[showcards N:S2,DA,DK,D8 E:SK,DJ,DT,D7 S:SQ,D5,D4,C7 W:SJ,ST,HQ,D2]

Unblocking the \SA to create a Threat out of your \SQ is the Vienna Coup.

As you see, South was able to find discards on your first three trump leads, but when you play the \C7 and discard dummy's \S2 he is squeezed.

He can see that if he discards a \D dummy will be high, so he will probably throw the \SK in hopes that his partner holds the \SQ. But you have that card and you make the slam. 

As an afterthought to this Deal, let us suppose you were playing 6NT rather than 6\C.

The only difference would be that to rectify the count you would have to hold up once on the opening \HK.}
[Play "W"]HK

