[Student "S"]
{West is to play 3NT. North leads the \S3. South plays the \S5.

From the opening lead of \S3 and South's play of \S5 you should have deduced that North held five \Ss to the A K. Therefore if you lose a trick in any other suit North will be able to take 4 \S tricks and defeat you.

You have 8 winners, and if South holds 4+ \Hs AND 3+ \Ds then only he can guard the two suits.

But how can you squeeze him? 

The answer to that question is that <b>YOU</b> cannot squeeze him.

But maybe you can make his partner do the job for you.

At trick 2 you play a \S. 

Of course North will win this with his \SK.

And he will no doubt continue with the \SA and \S9.

You discard 2 \Ds from dummy and a \C from your hand.

South cannot spare either a \H or a \D so he also throws a \C. 

***Remember this position***

North will almost surely cash his \S2.

You and dummy both discard a \C and South also must discard a \C.

It doesn't matter what North plays next, lets say it is a \C. 

In your hand with the \CK, you now play the \CA.

South is truly squeezed. If he discards a \H, dummy's \H5 will become a winner. but if he discards a \D then you will get a third \D trick and the contract.

Since it was North who started the squeeze by cashing his last \S, this is called a Suicide Squeeze.<b>BUT</b>, what if North had not cashed that \S? 

***Here is the position you were supposed to remember***

Suppose North is a really expert defender and avoids the Suicide Squeeze by just refusing to cash his winning \S. It doesn't matter what else he plays instead, so let us assume it is a \C.

You win in your hand and establish a \D winner by playing \DA, \DK, and a small \D. South wins but cannot reach his partner's hand for that good \S.

So you establish a \D winner and make your contract.}
[Play "W"]S3

